The first step is making sure that the repository is cloned properly.  It should look like:![][image1]

The next step is to make sure that both the Unreal Engine that the project is on currently and the Unreal Engine version that you want to update to are installed along with Visual Studio 2022\.

Right click on PlayerWONSDK.uproject (make sure to “Show more options” if on Windows 11). The first thing we’ll want to do is generate the visual studio project files.![][image2]

This will make sure we have all the code, and will generate a visual studio solution file in the project. From there we can right click the PlayerWONSDK.uproject again and go to Switch Unreal Engine Version.  
  ![][image3]

There are two ways to open the project. The first is by double clicking on the PlayerWONSDK.sln file, making sure that PlayerWONSDK is the Startup Project and that Visual Studio is set for Development Editor or Debug Editor.  Run the code and, as long as it can compile correctly, the Unreal Engine editor will load the project. Please refer to this documentation for Visual Studio setup for opening a project (which also covers how to build and open a project in XCode): [Epic's Documentation](https://dev.epicgames.com/documentation/en-us/unreal-engine/building-unreal-engine-from-source)

The other way to open the project is to double click on PlayerWONSDK.uproject. This will bring up the editor without opening the code first. Once in the editor you will need to click the compile button so that the project compiles correctly.
